hook.real_world_problem:
Flipkart calls a recommendation engine for 'You may also like' products. Occasionally, the recommendation engine hangs for 30 seconds:

```
Without timeout:
  Thread waits 30 seconds per recommendation call
  500 concurrent users × 30s = 15,000 thread-seconds blocked
  Thread pool exhausts → product pages fail to load entirely

With 2-second timeout:
  Thread waits max 2 seconds → TimeoutException → fallback
  Fallback: return bestsellers from last 24h (cached)
  Product page loads in 2.1 seconds instead of 30+ seconds
  User: sees 'Bestsellers' instead of personalized recommendations — acceptable!
```

```java
@TimeLimiter(name = "recommendations", fallbackMethod = "bestsellers")
@CircuitBreaker(name = "recommendations")
public CompletableFuture<List<Product>> getRecommendations(String userId) {
    return CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> recEngine.forUser(userId));
}

private CompletableFuture<List<Product>> bestsellers(String userId, Exception e) {
    return CompletableFuture.completedFuture(cachedBestsellers.get());
}
```

concept_explanation.timelimiter:
**@TimeLimiter — bound external call duration:**

```yaml
resilience4j:
  timelimiter:
    instances:
      recommendations:
        timeoutDuration: 2s    # max 2 seconds
        cancelRunningFuture: true  # cancel the CompletableFuture on timeout
```

```java
// @TimeLimiter REQUIRES CompletableFuture return type:
@TimeLimiter(name = "recommendations", fallbackMethod = "bestsellersFallback")
@CircuitBreaker(name = "recommendations")
public CompletableFuture<List<Product>> getRecommendations(String userId) {
    return CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> recEngine.forUser(userId));
    // If this takes > 2s: TimeoutException → bestsellersFallback() called
    // cancelRunningFuture=true: the future is cancelled (thread interrupted)
}

private CompletableFuture<List<Product>> bestsellersFallback(
        String userId, Exception e) {
    // Called on TimeoutException or CircuitBreaker open:
    return CompletableFuture.completedFuture(
        productCache.getBestsellers());
}
```

concept_explanation.fallback_strategies:
**Fallback strategies by use case:**

```java
// 1. STATIC DEFAULT — simplest, always works:
private int deliveryEstimateFallback(String id, Exception e) {
    return 45;  // 45-minute default — never fails
}

// 2. CACHED DATA — last known good value:
private List<Restaurant> restaurantFallback(String city, Exception e) {
    List<Restaurant> cached = redisCache.get("restaurants:" + city);
    return cached != null ? cached : List.of();
}

// 3. DEGRADED MODE — partial functionality:
private SeatMap seatMapFallback(String eventId, Exception e) {
    return SeatMap.zonePricing(eventId);  // simple zones, not interactive
}

// 4. FAIL FAST — critical path, surface the error:
private PaymentResult paymentFallback(ChargeRequest req, Exception e) {
    // Payment is critical — don't silently degrade
    throw new PaymentServiceException("Payment service unavailable", e);
}

// 5. QUEUE FOR RETRY — eventual consistency:
private void notificationFallback(String userId, String msg, Exception e) {
    retryQueue.offer(new RetryItem(userId, msg));
    // Will be retried when service recovers
}
```

concept_explanation.connection_vs_read:
**Connection timeout vs read timeout:**

```java
// RestTemplate configuration (connection vs read timeout):
// Connection timeout: how long to wait to ESTABLISH the TCP connection
// Read timeout: how long to wait for the SERVER to respond after connection

@Bean
public RestTemplate restTemplate() {
    var factory = new SimpleClientHttpRequestFactory();
    factory.setConnectTimeout(2000);  // 2s: fail if can't connect
    factory.setReadTimeout(5000);     // 5s: fail if server doesn't respond
    return new RestTemplate(factory);
}

// @TimeLimiter: wraps at the application level
// HTTP timeout: set at the HTTP client level
// Use BOTH: HTTP timeout prevents thread blocking;
//           @TimeLimiter + CB tracks failures for circuit opening
```

